An \emph{integer programming game} with $n$ players is a noncooperative game where the $S_i$ of actions for each player $i$ is the set of lattice points inside a polytope; that is,
\begin{equation}\label{eq:strategySets}
S_i=P_i\cap\Z^{d_i}
\end{equation}
where $P_i = \{\ve x \in \R^{d_i}:M_i\ve x \le \ve b_i\}$ is a rational polytope.

Let $I = \{1,\dots,n\}$ denote the set of players. The set $S$ of action profiles $\ve s = (\ve s_1,\ldots,\ve s_n)$ is the Cartesian product of the $S_i$'s:
$$S=\prod_{i=1}^n S_i \subseteq \Z^d$$
where $d = d_1+\cdots+d_n$. The payoff functions are integer-valued of the form $u_i:S\rightarrow \Z$ for $i \in I$.

An integer-valued payoff function $u:S\rightarrow \Z$ of a game is a \emph{difference of piecewise-linear convex functions} or \emph{DPLC} function if it can be expressed as:
\begin{equation*}
u(\ve s) = \max_{k\in K} f_k(\ve s) - \max_{l \in L} g_l(\ve s)
\end{equation*}
where the $f_k$ and $g_l$ are affine functions with integer coefficients and where $K$ and $L$ are finite index sets. We refer to the $f_k$ as the ``convex" pieces of $u$ and the $g_l$ as the ``concave" pieces of $u$.

